        <article class="content">
        <div class="section-pop">vibe check</div>
        <h2>String Switch Statements</h2>
        <p>The <code>vibe_check</code> for strings in CURSED is like that friend who knows exactly which TikTok sound matches your personality. It's the elite way to handle multiple string comparisons without all that <code>if</code> statement drama.</p>

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-title">Basic String Switch</div>
          <pre><code><span class="keyword">vibe_check</span> username {  <span class="comment">fr fr check the username's vibe</span>
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "admin":
        vibez.spill("You have all privileges")
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "moderator":
        vibez.spill("You can manage content")
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "user":
        vibez.spill("Welcome back!")
    <span class="keyword">basic</span>:
        vibez.spill("Unknown user type")
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <h3>ud83dudd25 Why It's Giving</h3>
        <p>String switch statements are a core feature that make string processing in CURSED absolutely bussin':</p>

        <div class="feature-box">
          <ul>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">ud83dudcbb</span> <strong>Clean AF:</strong> Way more readable than nested <code>if/else</code> statements</li>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">u26a1ufe0f</span> <strong>High Performance:</strong> Optimized string comparisons under the hood</li>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">ud83euddd0</span> <strong>Flexible Moods:</strong> Multiple string values per case</li>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">ud83dude0e</span> <strong>Fall Through:</strong> Cases can fall through without explicit breaks</li>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">ud83dudd27</span> <strong>Full Control:</strong> Break out of cases when needed with <code>ghosted</code></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>Advanced Features</h3>
        <p>Let's level up your <code>vibe_check</code> game with these pro strats:</p>

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-title">Multiple Values Per Case</div>
          <pre><code><span class="keyword">vibe_check</span> dayOfWeek {  <span class="comment">fr fr group similar vibes together</span>
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday":
        vibez.spill("Weekday grind")
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "Saturday", "Sunday":
        vibez.spill("Weekend mode activated")
    <span class="keyword">basic</span>:
        vibez.spill("Time isn't real anyway")
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-title">Fallthrough Between Cases</div>
          <pre><code><span class="keyword">vibe_check</span> errorCode {  <span class="comment">fr fr letting cases fall through</span>
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "404":
        vibez.spill("Page not found")
        <span class="comment">fr fr falls through to next case - no ghosted statement</span>
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "500":
        vibez.spill("Server error")
        <span class="keyword">ghosted</span>  <span class="comment">fr fr stops here, won't go to next case</span>
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "403":
        vibez.spill("Forbidden access")
    <span class="keyword">basic</span>:
        vibez.spill("Unknown error")
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="info-callout">
          <h3>ud83euddd0 The Tea on String Comparison</h3>
          <p>Under the hood, CURSED uses the C standard library's <code>strcmp</code> function to compare strings. This means the comparisons are:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Case-sensitive:</strong> "Hello" u2260 "hello"</li>
            <li><strong>Lexicographical:</strong> Character-by-character comparison</li>
            <li><strong>Null-terminated:</strong> Strings end with a null byte</li>
          </ul>
          <p>So make sure your vibes match exactly, bestie!</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Use Cases That Eat</h3>
        <p>String switches are perfect for when you're dealing with text inputs like:</p>

        <div class="steps-container">
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-number">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h4>Command Processing</h4>
              <p>Parsing user commands in a CLI or chat application</p>
              <div class="code-block mini">
                <pre><code><span class="keyword">vibe_check</span> command {
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "help": showHelp()
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "exit": exitApp()
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "clear": clearScreen()
}</code></pre>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-number">2</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h4>HTTP Request Handling</h4>
              <p>Routing API endpoints based on paths</p>
              <div class="code-block mini">
                <pre><code><span class="keyword">vibe_check</span> endpoint {
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "/users": handleUsers()
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "/products": handleProducts()
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "/auth": handleAuth()
}</code></pre>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-number">3</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h4>Configuration Processing</h4>
              <p>Handling different config settings by name</p>
              <div class="code-block mini">
                <pre><code><span class="keyword">vibe_check</span> setting {
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "theme": setTheme(value)
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "language": setLanguage(value)
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "volume": setVolume(parseFloat(value))
}</code></pre>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="warning-box">
          <h4>u26a0ufe0f Avoid These Bad Vibes</h4>
          <p>Even though string switches are elite, there are some situations where they're just not it:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Performance-critical loops:</strong> If you're comparing the same strings thousands of times in a hot loop, consider caching the result or using enums</li>
            <li><strong>Case-insensitive matching:</strong> String switch is case-sensitive by default, so you'd need to manually convert strings</li>
            <li><strong>Pattern matching:</strong> If you need regex or partial matching, string switch isn't built for that (yet ud83dude09)</li>
            <li><strong>Empty string edge cases:</strong> Be careful with empty strings as they can behave unexpectedly</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>Under The Hood</h3>
        <p>For the real ones who want to know how it works:</p>

        <div class="code-block">
          <div class="code-title">The Compiler Magic</div>
          <pre><code><span class="comment">fr fr What the compiler generates (simplified)</span>

<span class="comment">fr fr For a switch like:</span>
<span class="keyword">vibe_check</span> str {
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "A": actionA()
    <span class="keyword">mood</span> "B": actionB()
}

<span class="comment">fr fr Gets transformed into something like:</span>
<span class="keyword">lowkey</span> strcmp(str, "A") == 0 {
    actionA()
} <span class="keyword">highkey</span> <span class="keyword">lowkey</span> strcmp(str, "B") == 0 {
    actionB()
}</code></pre>
        </div>

        <p>The actual implementation is more optimized and uses LLVM's basic blocks for efficient control flow, but you get the idea!</p>

        <div class="pro-tip-box">
          <h4>u2728 Pro Tips</h4>
          <p>Level up your string switch game with these elite strats:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Group related cases to simplify your code (like error types, days of the week, etc.)</li>
            <li>For frequently used strings, consider creating constants to avoid typos</li>
            <li>Use fallthrough intentionally to create "stepped" processing of commands</li>
            <li>For case-insensitive matching, convert strings to lowercase before the switch</li>
            <li>When dealing with user input, always validate it before passing to a string switch</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>Future Enhancements</h3>
        <p>The CURSED team is working on these fire updates for string switch:</p>

        <div class="feature-box">
          <ul>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">ud83dudd25</span> <strong>Pattern Matching:</strong> Support for regex-based case values</li>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">ud83dudca1</span> <strong>Smart Optimization:</strong> Auto hash-based comparison for large switch statements</li>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">ud83dudcaa</span> <strong>String Interning:</strong> Performance boost for repeated switch values</li>
            <li><span class="emoji-tag">ud83eudd13</span> <strong>Expression Cases:</strong> Support for dynamic case values (not just literals)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

